---
import ClerriLayout from '../../layouts/ClerriLayout.astro';
---
<ClerriLayout title="Reporting Automation" section="reporting-automation">

<div class="page-head">
  <div class="page-eyebrow">Operations · Reporting &amp; Forecasting</div>
  <h1 class="page-title">Kill the spreadsheet — <em>live dashboards in the CRM.</em></h1>
  <p class="page-sub">The 2026 "Master" reporting workbook is a 32-tab manual ETL pipeline. Here's the layer map, why it exists, and the plan to replace it with native, filterable Salesforce + HubSpot dashboards — no more hand-pasting exports.</p>
</div>

<div class="page-body">

  <div class="takeaway">
    <span class="tk-lbl">Bottom line</span>
    <p>The workbook is a manual ETL pipeline: 7 exports hand-pasted on a schedule, "cleaned" by hand, then modeled into the leadership scorecard. Salesforce + HubSpot already talk natively (bidirectional sync) — the hard part isn't connecting them, it's defining clean funnel stages + UTM mapping, then building the dashboard in one home. That's a RevOps project that needs an owner, not a marketing-solo fix.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="progress-track"><div class="progress-fill" data-progress-fill="reporting-automation"></div></div>
  <p class="mono" style="font-size:0.75rem;color:var(--muted)">Progress: <span data-progress-here="reporting-automation">0 / 0</span></p>

  <h2>What the workbook actually is — <em>5 stacked layers.</em></h2>
  <div style="overflow-x:auto">
  <table class="rtable">
    <thead><tr><th>Layer</th><th>Tabs</th><th>What it does</th><th>Manual?</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><strong>1 · Raw</strong></td><td>Raw | Leads, MQL, SQL, Opportunity, Booked, Paid Clicks, Meta Clicks</td><td>Funnel exports from Salesforce/HubSpot + ad-spend from Google &amp; Meta</td><td><span class="tag tag-red">Hand-pasted</span></td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>2 · Cleaning</strong></td><td>Cleaned ___ columns; URL Builder, Approved UTM, URL Mapping, Mapping</td><td>Normalizes messy source/channel data after the fact</td><td><span class="tag tag-red">Hand-mapped</span></td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>3 · Model</strong></td><td>Inbound + Outbound Monthly, Goals by Channel / YOY, Sheet17</td><td>Applies conversion rates (Inbound 0.665 MQL→SQL, etc.) to compute goals + forecast by SMB/Enterprise</td><td><span class="tag tag-amber">Formula</span></td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>4 · Exec views</strong></td><td>ELT - Weekly Update, Daily Tracker</td><td>Leadership scorecard (Monthly / Target / % to Plan / YoY) + daily pacing</td><td><span class="tag tag-amber">Formula</span></td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>5 · Campaigns</strong></td><td>Third Party Calendar + Spend, Event Performance, Media Buy, Partner Affinity, Webinar Planning</td><td>Campaign-level spend + results tracking</td><td><span class="tag tag-red">Mixed manual</span></td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  </div>
  <p class="mono muted" style="font-size:0.8rem">Plus dead weight: "DONT EDIT…", "Dont Use Original…", "URL Builder (DEPRACTED)", and an empty "Organic-Paid | Third-Party Infl" tab — the tell that this grew with no clear owner.</p>

  <h2>The manual burden — <em>7 exports, every cycle.</em></h2>
  <div style="overflow-x:auto">
  <table class="rtable">
    <thead><tr><th>Tab</th><th>Source (proven by field names)</th><th>How it should flow instead</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Raw | Leads / MQL / SQL / Opportunity / Booked</td><td>Salesforce + HubSpot (<span class="mono">MQL: Entered</span>, <span class="mono">HS: First Conversion Date</span>)</td><td>Already in the CRM — never export</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Raw | Paid Clicks</td><td>Google Ads (<span class="mono">Cost Micros</span> is the API field)</td><td>Auto-connector (Supermetrics / Funnel.io)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Raw | Meta Clicks</td><td>Meta Ads (<span class="mono">Amount spent</span>, <span class="mono">Link clicks</span>)</td><td>Auto-connector (Supermetrics / Funnel.io)</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  </div>

  <h2>"Sync" is not "reporting" — <em>the distinction that decides everything.</em></h2>
  <div class="callout zest-hi">
    <p style="margin:0 0 0.6rem"><strong>Yes — Salesforce + HubSpot talk natively.</strong> HubSpot ships a certified, bidirectional integration (no middleware): contacts, companies, deals/opportunities, and activities sync both ways every few minutes, with field-level mapping you control.</p>
    <p style="margin:0"><strong>But syncing records ≠ a unified dashboard.</strong> Each system still reports on its own data. So the funnel dashboard has to be <em>built</em> in one home — with the other system's data synced in. You're choosing a reporting home, not just flipping on a connector. <span class="mono muted">(Verify HubSpot tier — the strong native sync + custom report builder generally need Marketing/Sales Hub Pro or Enterprise.)</span></p>
  </div>

  <h2>Where the dashboard lives — <em>A or B.</em></h2>
  <div class="grid-2">
    <div class="card">
      <span class="pill pill-zest">Option A</span>
      <h3 style="margin:0.5rem 0">Report in Salesforce</h3>
      <p style="font-size:0.9rem">Sync HubSpot marketing data into SFDC; build there. Native dashboards are filterable but somewhat static — <strong>CRM Analytics</strong> (paid add-on) is the genuinely interactive, drill-down experience.</p>
      <p class="mono" style="font-size:0.8rem;color:var(--clerri-green)">Best if leadership treats revenue/pipeline as the spine.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card" style="border:2px solid var(--clerri-green)">
      <span class="pill pill-green">Option B · Recommended</span>
      <h3 style="margin:0.5rem 0">Report in HubSpot</h3>
      <p style="font-size:0.9rem">Sync SFDC opportunity/booked data into HubSpot; build in the custom report builder. Dashboards are natively interactive + filterable, and marketing <strong>attribution</strong> (which channel sourced MQL→SQL→revenue) is far easier than in Salesforce.</p>
      <p class="mono" style="font-size:0.8rem;color:var(--clerri-green)">Best for a marketing-led funnel — which is yours.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <p style="font-size:0.9rem;color:var(--ink-soft);max-width:70ch"><strong>Recommendation:</strong> report the full funnel in HubSpot with Salesforce opportunity/booked synced in. It gives the channel-level MQL→SQL→Booked view this spreadsheet is faking, interactive + filterable, with no paid BI add-on. Reserve CRM Analytics for later only if leadership wants pipeline analytics Salesforce does deeper.</p>

  <h2>Operational prerequisites — <em>the RevOps work.</em></h2>
  <p style="color:var(--ink-soft);max-width:65ch">Automation amplifies clean data; it can't fix a messy funnel. These come before any dashboard. This is the "make it operational" layer.</p>
  <div data-section="reporting-automation"><label class="task"><input type="checkbox" data-track="ra-01-stages" data-section="reporting-automation" /><div class="task-content"><div class="task-title">Define funnel stages precisely: what <em>is</em> a Lead vs MQL vs SQL vs Opp vs Booked — and where each is set</div></div></label></div>
  <div data-section="reporting-automation"><label class="task"><input type="checkbox" data-track="ra-02-mapping" data-section="reporting-automation" /><div class="task-content"><div class="task-title">Map HubSpot lifecycle stage ↔ Salesforce stage so they agree</div></div></label></div>
  <div data-section="reporting-automation"><label class="task"><input type="checkbox" data-track="ra-03-utm" data-section="reporting-automation" /><div class="task-content"><div class="task-title">Enforce the UTM taxonomy at entry (locked URL builder + validation) so "Cleaned ___" columns become unnecessary</div></div></label></div>
  <div data-section="reporting-automation"><label class="task"><input type="checkbox" data-track="ra-04-connector" data-section="reporting-automation" /><div class="task-content"><div class="task-title">Audit the existing connector: is the native sync live, what tier, what syncs, which direction</div></div></label></div>
  <div data-section="reporting-automation"><label class="task"><input type="checkbox" data-track="ra-05-sourcetruth" data-section="reporting-automation" /><div class="task-content"><div class="task-title">Decide the source of truth per field (revenue = SFDC, marketing source = HubSpot)</div></div></label></div>
  <div data-section="reporting-automation"><label class="task"><input type="checkbox" data-track="ra-06-validate" data-section="reporting-automation" /><div class="task-content"><div class="task-title">Validate the conversion rates (0.665, 0.53, etc.) against real historical data, not assumptions</div></div></label></div>
  <div data-section="reporting-automation"><label class="task"><input type="checkbox" data-track="ra-07-sourcefields" data-section="reporting-automation" /><div class="task-content"><div class="task-title">Reconcile the THREE competing source fields (Original Source vs utm_source vs Lead Source) — declare one source of truth</div></div></label></div>

  <h2>Three competing source fields — <em>pick one source of truth.</em></h2>
  <div class="callout wine">
    <div class="lbl">Finding — surfaced by an inbound demo notification</div>
    <p style="margin:0 0 0.6rem">A RevOps Bot demo alert exposed a <strong>third</strong> source field: <code>Contact Lead Source: 421284932 - Email_marketing</code>. So "source" is tracked in three different places, and reporting is confused because nobody's declared which one wins:</p>
    <ul style="margin:0;padding-left:1.1rem;font-size:0.92rem;line-height:1.6">
      <li><strong>Original Source</strong> (HubSpot, auto) — channel category on every contact. <em>Reliable for channel-level reporting.</em></li>
      <li><strong>utm_source</strong> (campaign tags) — only on tagged-link arrivals, and a governance mess (fb vs facebook, year suffixes). <em>Campaign detail only, after cleanup.</em></li>
      <li><strong>Lead Source</strong> (the new one) — the numeric-ID prefix suggests a <strong>Salesforce picklist synced into HubSpot</strong>. Potentially more intentional, but verify before trusting.</li>
    </ul>
    <p style="margin:0.6rem 0 0;font-size:0.92rem"><strong>Action:</strong> pull <code>Lead Source</code>'s fill-rate + value distribution (consistently populated? what values? SFDC-synced?), then declare ONE field the reporting source of truth and map the others to it. Three competing fields = the confusion you're feeling.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>Marketing Diagnostic Dashboard — <em>build this to see the current state.</em></h2>
  <p style="color:var(--ink-soft);max-width:70ch">One dashboard, five questions: funnel shape, where contacts come from, is the data trustworthy, does it connect to revenue, what's the agency doing. Report on <code>Lifecycle Stage</code> + <code>Original Source</code> (the reliable fields). Build in order.</p>
  <div style="overflow-x:auto">
  <table class="rtable">
    <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Report</th><th>How to build it</th><th>What to look for</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>1</td><td><strong>Lifecycle funnel</strong></td><td>Funnel report: Lead→MQL→SQL→Opp→Customer + conversion rates</td><td>A stage where everything dies (broken handoff/definition); near-zero stages (unused); sane MQL→SQL ratio</td></tr>
      <tr><td>2</td><td><strong>Acquisition over time</strong></td><td>Contact create date, monthly (12-24mo), broken down by Original Source</td><td>Offline-import spikes (big list dumps); is <em>digital</em> acquisition growing or flat</td></tr>
      <tr><td>3</td><td><strong>MQLs by source</strong></td><td>Became-MQL date, monthly, broken down by Original Source</td><td>Did 39→57 happen; which channel drove it (Organic = maybe agency; Paid/Events/Offline = not)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>4</td><td><strong>Data completeness</strong></td><td>Counts by Lifecycle Stage; contacts with no Owner / no Source / blank lifecycle</td><td>% with blank lifecycle (funnel built on sand); % offline (~97%); orphaned contacts</td></tr>
      <tr><td>5</td><td><strong>Deals → revenue</strong></td><td>Deals by stage, by Original Source, win rate, avg sales cycle</td><td>Which sources produce closed-won; pipeline coverage; cycle length by segment</td></tr>
      <tr><td>6</td><td><strong>The 89K offline</strong></td><td>Offline-source contacts grouped by Original Source Drill-Down 1/2 (or import/list)</td><td>Purchased lists? event scans? an integration? the Kleer/Membersy migration?</td></tr>
      <tr><td>7</td><td><strong>utm_source mess</strong></td><td>Non-offline contacts grouped by utm_source</td><td>Quantify the fragmentation for the cleanup + the vendor audit</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  </div>
  <div class="grid-2">
    <div class="card"><h4>⚠️ Tier caveat</h4><p style="font-size:0.875rem">Multi-touch <em>revenue</em> attribution needs Marketing Hub <strong>Enterprise</strong> — verify the tier. The funnel + everything above works on <strong>Pro</strong>.</p></div>
    <div class="card"><h4>⚠️ Garbage-in caveat</h4><p style="font-size:0.875rem">Reports are only as good as the stage/source definitions. If numbers look wild, it's a data-definition problem — that's the finding, not a report bug. Take it to the ops consultant.</p></div>
  </div>
  <p style="color:var(--ink-soft);max-width:70ch;margin-top:0.5rem"><strong>Build checklist:</strong></p>
  <div data-section="reporting-automation"><label class="task"><input type="checkbox" data-track="dd-01-funnel" data-section="reporting-automation" /><div class="task-content"><div class="task-title">#1 Lifecycle funnel</div></div></label></div>
  <div data-section="reporting-automation"><label class="task"><input type="checkbox" data-track="dd-02-acquisition" data-section="reporting-automation" /><div class="task-content"><div class="task-title">#2 Acquisition over time by Original Source</div></div></label></div>
  <div data-section="reporting-automation"><label class="task"><input type="checkbox" data-track="dd-03-mqls" data-section="reporting-automation" /><div class="task-content"><div class="task-title">#3 MQLs over time by source (tests the agency claim)</div></div></label></div>
  <div data-section="reporting-automation"><label class="task"><input type="checkbox" data-track="dd-04-completeness" data-section="reporting-automation" /><div class="task-content"><div class="task-title">#4 Data completeness / hygiene</div></div></label></div>
  <div data-section="reporting-automation"><label class="task"><input type="checkbox" data-track="dd-05-deals" data-section="reporting-automation" /><div class="task-content"><div class="task-title">#5 Deals by source + stage + win rate</div></div></label></div>
  <div data-section="reporting-automation"><label class="task"><input type="checkbox" data-track="dd-06-offline" data-section="reporting-automation" /><div class="task-content"><div class="task-title">#6 The 89K offline breakdown</div></div></label></div>
  <div data-section="reporting-automation"><label class="task"><input type="checkbox" data-track="dd-07-utm" data-section="reporting-automation" /><div class="task-content"><div class="task-title">#7 utm_source mess (cleanup + audit ammo)</div></div></label></div>

  <h2>Agenda for your ops-consultant conversation</h2>
  <p style="color:var(--ink-soft);max-width:65ch">He's likely the one doing the manual exports today — so he holds the ground truth on how the data actually flows. This is a discovery conversation, not a confrontation. Listen for where the real friction is.</p>

  <h3>The connector &amp; data flow</h3>
  <div class="card qa">
    <p class="q">Is the native HubSpot–Salesforce integration live today, or is anything held together with middleware (Zapier, n8n, manual)?</p>
    <p class="ctx">Establishes whether we're configuring an existing sync or building one.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="card qa">
    <p class="q">Walk me through a lead's full path — where it enters, and how it moves Lead → MQL → SQL → Opp → Booked across both systems.</p>
    <p class="ctx">Reveals which system owns which stage, and where data gets stuck or re-keyed.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="card qa">
    <p class="q">What HubSpot tier are we on? What objects and fields sync today, and in which direction?</p>
    <p class="ctx">Tier gates the native reporting; sync scope tells us what's already usable.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>Stages &amp; definitions</h3>
  <div class="card qa">
    <p class="q">How is an MQL defined right now — and is that the same definition in HubSpot and Salesforce?</p>
    <p class="ctx">If the two disagree, every funnel number is suspect. This is the root of most reporting pain.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="card qa">
    <p class="q">Why do the "Cleaned" source/channel columns exist — what's dirty about the raw data?</p>
    <p class="ctx">Points straight at the UTM-enforcement gap we need to close.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="card qa">
    <p class="q">What is "Contact Lead Source," is it synced from Salesforce, and who/what sets it — vs. Original Source and utm_source?</p>
    <p class="ctx">Resolves the three-source-field confusion. The numeric-ID format on the demo alert smells like an SFDC picklist sync.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>The manual work &amp; the bridge</h3>
  <div class="card qa">
    <p class="q">Exactly what do you export and paste each cycle, how long does it take, and what breaks most often?</p>
    <p class="ctx">Quantifies the time we'd reclaim and surfaces the fragile spots.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="card qa">
    <p class="q">While we fix native reporting, can we auto-feed the Raw tabs with a connector (Coefficient for CRM, Supermetrics for ad spend) so you stop pasting now?</p>
    <p class="ctx">A bridge that buys relief immediately without waiting on the full rebuild.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="card qa">
    <p class="q">Who should own this funnel + dashboard going forward?</p>
    <p class="ctx">The real first step. Unowned infrastructure is why we have a 32-tab file. Likely RevOps / SFDC admin.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>The phased plan</h2>
  <div class="grid-3">
    <div class="card"><span class="pill pill-mint">Now</span><h4 style="margin:0.5rem 0">Stop the bleeding</h4><p style="font-size:0.875rem">Coefficient (CRM→Sheets) + Supermetrics (ad spend) auto-feed the Raw tabs. No more pasting while we fix the foundation. ~$100-300/mo.</p></div>
    <div class="card"><span class="pill pill-zest">Next</span><h4 style="margin:0.5rem 0">Fix the foundation</h4><p style="font-size:0.875rem">Clean stage definitions, enforce UTMs, audit the connector, set source-of-truth. The prerequisites above. RevOps-owned.</p></div>
    <div class="card"><span class="pill pill-wine">Then</span><h4 style="margin:0.5rem 0">Native dashboards</h4><p style="font-size:0.875rem">Build the full funnel + forecast in HubSpot (SFDC synced in). Retire the spreadsheet as source of truth. Interactive, filterable, no paste.</p></div>
  </div>

  <div class="note-block">
    <div class="note-label">Reporting notes <span class="note-saved">✓ saved</span></div>
    <textarea data-note="reporting-automation-notes" placeholder="Ops consultant answers, connector status, stage definitions, who owns it, decisions..."></textarea>
  </div>

  <div class="topic-foot">
    <a href="/clerri/vendor-audit"><span class="dir">← Prev</span><span class="name">Vendor Audit</span></a>
    <a href="/clerri/partners"><span class="dir">Next →</span><span class="name">Partnership Targets</span></a>
  </div>

</div>

<style>
  .rtable { width:100%; border-collapse:collapse; font-size:0.88rem; margin:0.5rem 0 0.75rem; }
  .rtable th, .rtable td { text-align:left; padding:0.55rem 0.7rem; border-bottom:1px solid var(--cotton-dark); vertical-align:top; }
  .rtable th { font-family:'JetBrains Mono', monospace; font-size:0.68rem; letter-spacing:0.07em; text-transform:uppercase; color:var(--clerri-green); }
  .rtable .mono { font-family:'JetBrains Mono', monospace; font-size:0.8rem; }
  .rtable .muted, .muted { color:var(--muted); }
  .tag { display:inline-block; font-size:0.7rem; font-weight:700; padding:0.12rem 0.5rem; border-radius:1rem; white-space:nowrap; }
  .tag-red { background:#f3d2d2; color:#8a2d3f; }
  .tag-amber { background:#ffe7a3; color:#5c4500; }
  .qa { margin-bottom:0.75rem; }
  .qa .q { font-weight:600; color:var(--ink); margin:0 0 0.4rem; font-size:0.95rem; }
  .qa .ctx { color:var(--muted); margin:0; font-size:0.875rem; font-style:italic; }
</style>

</ClerriLayout>
